President Cyril Ramaphosa has not left a single written parliamentary question unanswered this year, according to statistics released by Parliament yesterday. Statistics yesterday showed that the executive received 1031 written questions from MPs and that they answered more than 60% – leaving a total of 321 questions unanswered. The president who will answer questions in the National Assembly today has replied to each of the 10 written questions sent to his office. Public Enterprises Minister Pravin Gordan, according to the figures released, also has a thrifty record – having replied to 30 of the 32 questions dispatched to his office. Health Minister Aaron Motsoaledi received the most written questions, fielding a total of 216 and replying to 118. According to the report, some ministers did not reply to a single written question. They include Economic Development Minister Ebrahim Patel, Defence Minister Nosiviwe MapisaNqakula, Energy Minister Jeff Radebe, Justice and Correctional Services Minister Michael Masutha and Home Affairs Minister Malusi Gigaba. However, the record also shows that Gigaba had to face the most oral questions among members of the executive and that he replied to eight out of the 10 questions he received. Masutha left nine verbal questions unanswered, while Mapisa-Nqakula did not answer one of her six questions. –DENNIS CRUYWAGEN